# batch-pr-rebase-workflow — Version History

## v2.2.0 (2026-04-22)

**Changed by:** ProjectHermes ~30 PR bulk rebase session (all PRs touched same 3 core files)
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Added `(11)` trigger to description: "10+ branches all conflict on same 3-5 core files — take HEAD"
- Added new "When to Use" bullet for same-file serial merge scenario
- Added Phase 3.6: Take-HEAD Batch Rebase for Same-File Conflicts — full batch script with Safety Net workaround, empty commit handling, and GIT_EDITOR=true pattern
- Added 3 new Failed Attempts rows: `git checkout HEAD -- file` Safety Net block + `/tmp` workaround; sub-agent delegation failure for same-file conflicts; semantic merge waste when main is already superset
- Added ProjectHermes to Verified On table
- Added `~30 PRs, same 3-5 files` row to Session Scale Reference

### Why
Rebasing ~30 open PRs in ProjectHermes where every PR touched `server.py`, `config.py`, and `publisher.py`. Classic "everyone touches the same files" scenario — by PR #10, origin/main already contains the union of all prior merged features. Taking HEAD for all conflicted core files is always correct; the branch's unique value is in its own new files and tests only. The Safety Net block on `git checkout HEAD -- file` required the `/tmp` workaround documented in Phase 3.6.

---

## v2.1.0 (2026-04-12)

**Changed by:** ProjectScylla dependabot PR sequential rebase session
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed
- Added 4 new Failed Attempts rows: `gh pr checkout` stale branch trap, `git reset --hard` Safety Net block, parallel agents in shared working tree, and parallel rebase without waiting for merges

### Why
Rebasing 5 dependabot PRs revealed that `gh pr checkout` reuses existing local branches — when prior agents had checked out different branches under the same name, later agents picked up the wrong commits. The fix is always to use `git worktree add /tmp/<name> origin/<branch>` for clean isolation. Also documented the sequential-rebase lesson: rebasing multiple PRs that touch shared files (pixi.lock, pyproject.toml) in parallel causes them to immediately go DIRTY again as each merge advances main.

---

